All right, there's the disclosure statement.

11
00:00:27.600 --> 00:00:30.633
If you wanna read the learning objectives, please do so.

12
00:00:31.530 --> 00:00:33.300
All right, first things first, we have a lot to cover.

13
00:00:33.300 --> 00:00:37.020
ACS, all of acute coronary syndrome

14
00:00:37.020 --> 00:00:39.510
and then hyperlipidemia all bundled into one.

15
00:00:39.510 --> 00:00:42.660
So first things first, acute coronary syndrome

16
00:00:42.660 --> 00:00:44.730
and like Dr. Weiss Miller mentioned,

17
00:00:44.730 --> 00:00:46.680
I'm a residency program director.

18
00:00:46.680 --> 00:00:48.270
I'll mention some of the things that I try

19
00:00:48.270 --> 00:00:50.820
and coach our residents to not do.

20
00:00:50.820 --> 00:00:53.040
One is we've tried to get away from,

21
00:00:53.040 --> 00:00:56.820
we admitted to rule out MI, no, we evaluate

22
00:00:56.820 --> 00:00:58.470
for acute coronary syndrome.

23
00:00:58.470 --> 00:00:59.700
There's other things

24
00:00:59.700 --> 00:01:02.070
that fall under ACS besides just an MI.

25
00:01:02.070 --> 00:01:05.520
So ACS is really three things under the umbrella.

26
00:01:05.520 --> 00:01:07.950
Number one is unstable angina,

27
00:01:07.950 --> 00:01:10.770
number two NSTEMI or non-ST elevation MI.

28
00:01:10.770 --> 00:01:13.200
And number three is ST elevation MI.

29
00:01:13.200 --> 00:01:16.290
And really, when we admit someone who has some vague symptom

30
00:01:16.290 --> 00:01:18.180
between their chin and their belly button,

31
00:01:18.180 --> 00:01:20.310
ideally with, you know, all the, you know,

32
00:01:20.310 --> 00:01:22.050
classic symptoms in the Levine sign,

33
00:01:22.050 --> 00:01:23.160
remember the flexed fist

34
00:01:23.160 --> 00:01:25.710
or the clenched fist over the chest.

35
00:01:25.710 --> 00:01:28.413
Then we want to evaluate for acute coronary syndrome.

36
00:01:29.610 --> 00:01:30.900
Typically, it is,

37
00:01:30.900 --> 00:01:33.180
well it's always a supply demand mismatch.

38
00:01:33.180 --> 00:01:34.950
Typically it's a reduced supply.

39
00:01:34.950 --> 00:01:36.480
You've got a vessel that got occluded,

40
00:01:36.480 --> 00:01:38.730
therefore a supply has decreased.

41
00:01:38.730 --> 00:01:40.800
But you can also see increased demand.

42
00:01:40.800 --> 00:01:42.060
For example, take someone

43
00:01:42.060 --> 00:01:46.410
who had a 50% stenosis in a coronary artery,

44
00:01:46.410 --> 00:01:48.900
everything is fine if they can slowly walk through Walmart

45
00:01:48.900 --> 00:01:52.230
and do just dandy until they develop atrial fibrillation

46
00:01:52.230 --> 00:01:54.450
or a flutter with two to one conduction,

47
00:01:54.450 --> 00:01:57.180
and suddenly they've got a heart rate of 140.

48
00:01:57.180 --> 00:01:59.100
And that 50% stenosis,

49
00:01:59.100 --> 00:02:03.180
which was not flow limiting at a heart rate of 95,

50
00:02:03.180 --> 00:02:06.060
letting them walk through Walmart, is now flow limiting

51
00:02:06.060 --> 00:02:07.950
with a heart rate of 140.

52
00:02:07.950 --> 00:02:10.530
The lesion didn't change, the demand changed,

53
00:02:10.530 --> 00:02:12.720
and you have a increased demand.

54
00:02:12.720 --> 00:02:14.910
In essence, a supply demand mismatch.

55
00:02:14.910 --> 00:02:18.210
The issue is not the vessel, the issue was increased demand.

56
00:02:18.210 --> 00:02:21.300
So usually it's a supply issue, you know, a plaque ruptures,

57
00:02:21.300 --> 00:02:24.900
and most commonly that's an occlusive thrombus on top

58
00:02:24.900 --> 00:02:27.900
of a disrupted plaque.

59
00:02:27.900 --> 00:02:29.160
The difficult thing though is

60
00:02:29.160 --> 00:02:32.100
that little bullet point there, nearly 50%

61
00:02:32.100 --> 00:02:34.620
of plaque ruptures occur at sites

62
00:02:34.620 --> 00:02:36.903
that have less than 50% narrowing.

63
00:02:37.770 --> 00:02:38.970
Think about that for just a minute.

64
00:02:38.970 --> 00:02:40.380
If you do exercise stress tests,

65
00:02:40.380 --> 00:02:42.660
you put people on the treadmill, you exercise them,

66
00:02:42.660 --> 00:02:45.120
you're looking for 80 to 90% stenosis.

67
00:02:45.120 --> 00:02:47.490
Those are the ones that are gonna cause angina.

68
00:02:47.490 --> 00:02:50.670
50% stenosis doesn't cause angina

69
00:02:50.670 --> 00:02:53.520
until either a little bit occludes

70
00:02:53.520 --> 00:02:55.020
or it a lot occludes,

71
00:02:55.020 --> 00:02:57.180
when the plaque ruptures, you have a thrombus

72
00:02:57.180 --> 00:02:59.580
that now acutely closes that vessel

73
00:02:59.580 --> 00:03:02.880
and now you've got an entirely closed vessel.

74
00:03:02.880 --> 00:03:05.790
The problem is that the 50% lesions are not the ones

75
00:03:05.790 --> 00:03:06.990
that are easy to detect,

76
00:03:06.990 --> 00:03:09.450
but they're also the most vulnerable lesions.

77
00:03:09.450 --> 00:03:11.970
If you think about the life history

78
00:03:11.970 --> 00:03:14.940
of atherosclerotic plaque, it starts off with a fatty streak

79
00:03:14.940 --> 00:03:16.530
and then you get inflammation.

80
00:03:16.530 --> 00:03:18.300
Remember the lipid related macrophages,

81
00:03:18.300 --> 00:03:20.910
which are foam cells, you end up getting a more

82
00:03:20.910 --> 00:03:24.120
of a more inflammatory response, at that point,

83
00:03:24.120 --> 00:03:26.100
there's still a fairly thin fibrous cap.

84
00:03:26.100 --> 00:03:29.730
So the lesion is inflammatory and unstable.

85
00:03:29.730 --> 00:03:33.720
As that lesion progresses, it becomes less inflammatory,

86
00:03:33.720 --> 00:03:36.330
more calcified, more stable,

87
00:03:36.330 --> 00:03:38.940
and it has a thicker fibrous cap.

88
00:03:38.940 --> 00:03:42.600
So the progressive occlusion of the vessel leads

89
00:03:42.600 --> 00:03:45.270
to more angina and people are more symptomatic

90
00:03:45.270 --> 00:03:46.830
from an angina standpoint.

91
00:03:46.830 --> 00:03:50.070
But the plaque itself is actually physiologically

92
00:03:50.070 --> 00:03:52.470
more stable and less likely to rupture.

93
00:03:52.470 --> 00:03:55.680
So differentiate in your mind the 50% stenosis.

94
00:03:55.680 --> 00:03:58.740
The smaller narrowing of the vessel are the ones

95
00:03:58.740 --> 00:03:59.850
that are more likely to rupture,

96
00:03:59.850 --> 00:04:02.250
more likely to cause acute coronary syndrome.

97
00:04:02.250 --> 00:04:04.740
The 80, 90% stenosis are the ones that are more likely

98
00:04:04.740 --> 00:04:07.413
to cause angina, but they're more stable lesions.

99
00:04:09.000 --> 00:04:10.260
Other potential etiologies.

100
00:04:10.260 --> 00:04:12.780
You can see arterial spasm on top of a plaque.

101
00:04:12.780 --> 00:04:15.750
Again, a 50% lesion with cocaine on top

102
00:04:15.750 --> 00:04:18.450
of it now becomes a 95% lesion

103
00:04:18.450 --> 00:04:20.730
and then it becomes occlusive.

104
00:04:20.730 --> 00:04:22.350
You can't even see normal coronary arteries

105
00:04:22.350 --> 00:04:24.630
that will spasm, arterial inflammation.

106
00:04:24.630 --> 00:04:26.850
Kawasaki being one of the prototypes there.

107
00:04:26.850 --> 00:04:29.610
And again, cocaine is a common trigger

108
00:04:29.610 --> 00:04:31.920
for a coronary spasm.

109
00:04:31.920 --> 00:04:34.080
Remember the nitroglycerin calcium channel blockers

110
00:04:34.080 --> 00:04:35.190
are the drugs of choice.

111
00:04:35.190 --> 00:04:38.100
We also use, interestingly enough, benzodiazepines for those

112
00:04:38.100 --> 00:04:40.260
of you that don't do a lot of work in the ED,

113
00:04:40.260 --> 00:04:42.360
taking care of people who inhale cocaine,

114
00:04:42.360 --> 00:04:43.890
then coming into my chest hurts.

115
00:04:43.890 --> 00:04:46.233
So well, stop doing the cocaine please.

116
00:04:48.390 --> 00:04:50.310
Acute coronary syndrome, so one stable angina

117
00:04:50.310 --> 00:04:52.980
and NSTEMI very closely related.

118
00:04:52.980 --> 00:04:55.463
Clinically you cannot tell the difference.

119
00:04:55.463 --> 00:04:57.960
Looking at the patient, listening to the history,

120
00:04:57.960 --> 00:04:59.700
looking at the EKG,

121
00:04:59.700 --> 00:05:03.780
the only differentiating factor is basically ischemia

122
00:05:03.780 --> 00:05:05.100
that is significant enough

123
00:05:05.100 --> 00:05:08.997
to cause myocardial necrosis equals NSTEMI,

124
00:05:08.997 --> 00:05:10.860
non-ST elevation MI.

125
00:05:10.860 --> 00:05:14.610
So that is the same symptoms except with enzymes.

126
00:05:14.610 --> 00:05:17.400
Same symptoms with no troponin leak,

127
00:05:17.400 --> 00:05:19.860
no enzymes equals unstable angina.

128
00:05:19.860 --> 00:05:22.800
That is the only differentiating factor.

129
00:05:22.800 --> 00:05:25.290
ST elevation MI, hopefully that's one

130
00:05:25.290 --> 00:05:27.900
that you can pick up fairly quickly on an EKG.

131
00:05:27.900 --> 00:05:29.460
My recommendation to our residents

132
00:05:29.460 --> 00:05:31.800
and I guess for everybody is be comfortable enough

133
00:05:31.800 --> 00:05:34.980
reading EKGs that within about 10 seconds you can take

134
00:05:34.980 --> 00:05:37.920
an EKG and decide is this normal enough

135
00:05:37.920 --> 00:05:41.790
that I can set it aside, do my thorough interpretation later

136
00:05:41.790 --> 00:05:43.200
or is this abnormal enough

137
00:05:43.200 --> 00:05:45.360
that has now become a decision point for me

138
00:05:45.360 --> 00:05:48.981
and I have to do something now based on this EKG.

139
00:05:48.981 --> 00:05:52.140
ST elevation MI, STEMI should be in that category

140
00:05:52.140 --> 00:05:53.793
of let's do something now.

141
00:05:55.860 --> 00:05:56.700
This is an important one.

142
00:05:56.700 --> 00:05:58.560
So I said that the differentiating factor

143
00:05:58.560 --> 00:05:59.730
between unstable angina

144
00:05:59.730 --> 00:06:04.260
and NSTEMI is biomarkers, enzymes, intracellular enzymes

145
00:06:04.260 --> 00:06:07.200
that are released when you have myocardial necrosis.

146
00:06:07.200 --> 00:06:09.000
So when muscle cells break apart,

147
00:06:09.000 --> 00:06:10.290
they release their little guts

148
00:06:10.290 --> 00:06:11.610
and their little guts have troponin

149
00:06:11.610 --> 00:06:12.960
among other things in them.

150
00:06:13.800 --> 00:06:17.790
We don't use CK and we don't use myoglobin often anymore.

151
00:06:17.790 --> 00:06:20.460
Troponin is really the biomarker of choice.

152
00:06:20.460 --> 00:06:22.530
Depending on your hospital, you may have troponin I,

153
00:06:22.530 --> 00:06:24.210
troponin T, it doesn't matter

154
00:06:24.210 --> 00:06:26.160
and they're both considered equivalent.

155
00:06:27.090 --> 00:06:29.640
The plus and minus troponin is takes about three

156
00:06:29.640 --> 00:06:31.320
to six hours to be released.

157
00:06:31.320 --> 00:06:33.510
So if you don't mind me pointing at this one,

158
00:06:33.510 --> 00:06:36.600
if you look at the very, very beginning of that graph,

159
00:06:36.600 --> 00:06:38.940
there is a little bit of lag time between the onset

160
00:06:38.940 --> 00:06:40.170
of myocardial necrosis

161
00:06:40.170 --> 00:06:42.900
and when troponin actually shows up in the serum

162
00:06:42.900 --> 00:06:44.460
and you can detect it.

163
00:06:44.460 --> 00:06:46.830
Which is why when someone is coming to the hospital

164
00:06:46.830 --> 00:06:49.380
with chest pain of recent start

165
00:06:49.380 --> 00:06:51.420
and they about an hour ago develop chest pain,

166
00:06:51.420 --> 00:06:52.800
you have to sit and watch 'em for a little while.

167
00:06:52.800 --> 00:06:54.540
You have to get serial troponins

168
00:06:54.540 --> 00:06:57.240
because you may be so early in that process

169
00:06:57.240 --> 00:06:59.390
that you're not gonna see the troponin yet.

170
00:07:00.480 --> 00:07:02.400
A plus and minus is that troponin stays

171
00:07:02.400 --> 00:07:03.510
around for a long time.

172
00:07:03.510 --> 00:07:05.850
Depending on the height of the troponin elevation,

173
00:07:05.850 --> 00:07:07.470
it may take up to two weeks

174
00:07:07.470 --> 00:07:09.903
before a troponin drops completely to zero.

175
00:07:10.800 --> 00:07:12.360
That becomes helpful, if someone says,

176
00:07:12.360 --> 00:07:13.860
a week ago I had symptoms

177
00:07:13.860 --> 00:07:16.710
and what happened a week ago, if they had an MI,

178
00:07:16.710 --> 00:07:18.090
their troponin is still gonna be up

179
00:07:18.090 --> 00:07:20.160
and you may still be able to detect that.

180
00:07:20.160 --> 00:07:21.450
The minus is if you're

181
00:07:21.450 --> 00:07:24.120
in this zone right over here a week

182
00:07:24.120 --> 00:07:26.790
or 10 days out, someone had an event,

183
00:07:26.790 --> 00:07:29.580
they're on the downside of their troponin release

184
00:07:29.580 --> 00:07:31.440
and now they come back in,

185
00:07:31.440 --> 00:07:32.940
they say, I've got this new chest pain.

186
00:07:32.940 --> 00:07:35.850
It feels just like it did a week ago.

187
00:07:35.850 --> 00:07:38.100
You check troponin, it's still up and you don't know if that

188
00:07:38.100 --> 00:07:39.690
because of the index event

189
00:07:39.690 --> 00:07:43.200
or are they're having another event in a secondary manner.

190
00:07:43.200 --> 00:07:45.030
So that's actually one of the few cases

191
00:07:45.030 --> 00:07:47.850
where CK-MB and myoglobin can be helpful.

192
00:07:47.850 --> 00:07:51.990
CK-MB is cardiac muscle specific, myoglobin is not.

193
00:07:51.990 --> 00:07:53.880
So if someone goes and runs a race,

194
00:07:53.880 --> 00:07:55.140
you know they run a marathon

195
00:07:55.140 --> 00:07:57.420
and you check their myoglobin, it's gonna be elevated.

196
00:07:57.420 --> 00:07:59.280
They're gonna tear apart some muscle

197
00:07:59.280 --> 00:08:00.810
from some physical event.

198
00:08:00.810 --> 00:08:03.210
You don't know if that's cardiac or whether that's skeletal.

199
00:08:03.210 --> 00:08:06.483
So CK is the one that is specifically cardiac.

200
00:08:08.063 --> 00:08:09.210
All right, so let's move on to a question.

201
00:08:09.210 --> 00:08:10.593
Pull out your devices.

202
00:08:11.550 --> 00:08:14.882
We've got a 52-year-old man who presents within 40,

203
00:08:14.882 --> 00:08:15.715
excuse me, with 45 minutes

204
00:08:15.715 --> 00:08:17.340
of squeezing substernal chest pressure,

205
00:08:17.340 --> 00:08:19.050
radiating to his left arm.

206
00:08:19.050 --> 00:08:21.090
You might even get the Levine sign.

207
00:08:21.090 --> 00:08:23.370
EKG from a physical two months ago is normal

208
00:08:23.370 --> 00:08:25.233
and this is his EKG.

209
00:08:26.520 --> 00:08:30.573
Take a moment, maybe 10 seconds to glance over that.

210
00:08:32.400 --> 00:08:35.400
See what you think, question is,

211
00:08:35.400 --> 00:08:37.650
what are you looking at basically?

212
00:08:37.650 --> 00:08:40.530
All right, so history

213
00:08:40.530 --> 00:08:41.790
and EKG are most consistent

214
00:08:41.790 --> 00:08:45.720
with which the following is this, A, esophageal spasm,

215
00:08:45.720 --> 00:08:50.280
B, STEMI, ST elevation MI, C, NSTEMI,

216
00:08:50.280 --> 00:08:53.313
non-ST elevation MI or was this pericarditis?

217
00:08:58.530 --> 00:09:02.190
So most are going with NSTEMI, esophageal spasm,

218
00:09:02.190 --> 00:09:04.410
I don't know that there are actually EKG findings

219
00:09:04.410 --> 00:09:06.870
that you would see with that.

220
00:09:06.870 --> 00:09:09.390
ST elevation MI, there were not ST elevations.

221
00:09:09.390 --> 00:09:12.210
So that crossed that one off the list, pericarditis,

222
00:09:12.210 --> 00:09:15.000
I will show you an example of in a little bit.

223
00:09:15.000 --> 00:09:18.360
So what was seen on this EKG in leads two

224
00:09:18.360 --> 00:09:21.780
and AVF, inferior leads some ST segment depression.

225
00:09:21.780 --> 00:09:24.690
Remember ST depression equals ischemia.

226
00:09:24.690 --> 00:09:26.610
There's also in the lateral precordia leads V five

227
00:09:26.610 --> 00:09:28.923
and V six some ST depression as well.

228
00:09:30.090 --> 00:09:32.010
One important thing when you're either doing

229
00:09:32.010 --> 00:09:34.290
an exercise stress test or looking at an EKG

230
00:09:34.290 --> 00:09:38.700
that shows ST segment depression and you're tempted to say,

231
00:09:38.700 --> 00:09:41.400
because I see ST depression in the inferior leads

232
00:09:41.400 --> 00:09:42.930
or in the lateral corneal leads,

233
00:09:42.930 --> 00:09:46.050
that should somehow correspond to either inferior

234
00:09:46.050 --> 00:09:48.030
or lateral ischemia.

235
00:09:48.030 --> 00:09:51.060
It doesn't correlate at least well,

236
00:09:51.060 --> 00:09:54.000
you can't necessarily look at the ischemic changes here

237
00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:55.440
and say with certainty

238
00:09:55.440 --> 00:09:58.710
or with a solid conclusion that those are the vessels,

239
00:09:58.710 --> 00:10:01.050
that's the area of heart that is truly ischemic.

240
00:10:01.050 --> 00:10:02.790
The repolarization abnormalities,

241
00:10:02.790 --> 00:10:05.970
the ST segment depression doesn't point well

242
00:10:05.970 --> 00:10:07.890
to the site of ischemia.

243
00:10:07.890 --> 00:10:10.290
You might say it's in those leads in the inferior

244
00:10:10.290 --> 00:10:11.370
and the lateral precordial leads,

245
00:10:11.370 --> 00:10:13.710
but it doesn't necessarily point to the vessel

246
00:10:13.710 --> 00:10:15.153
that is the culprit.

247
00:10:16.770 --> 00:10:18.303
All right, so next question.

248
00:10:19.230 --> 00:10:23.880
Now we've got a 72-year-old with NSTEMI who presents

249
00:10:23.880 --> 00:10:25.680
to your rural emergency room with onset

250
00:10:25.680 --> 00:10:27.840
of pain two hours ago.

251
00:10:27.840 --> 00:10:30.663
What is an appropriate immediate intervention?

252
00:10:32.220 --> 00:10:34.290
So would you give some metoprolol

253
00:10:34.290 --> 00:10:36.120
and we're assuming that it's got history now,

254
00:10:36.120 --> 00:10:37.722
we've got a positive troponin.

255
00:10:37.722 --> 00:10:41.730
Would you fibrinolyse within two hours,

256
00:10:41.730 --> 00:10:44.250
give an enteric-coated aspirin, 81 milligrams

257
00:10:44.250 --> 00:10:45.963
or a chewable aspirin?

258
00:10:51.870 --> 00:10:55.020
All right, excellent, most everyone is going with aspirin.

259
00:10:55.020 --> 00:10:57.390
So the reason for the enteric coated not being

260
00:10:57.390 --> 00:11:00.060
a good choice is you want the aspirin to work quickly.

261
00:11:00.060 --> 00:11:02.250
Enteric coated aspirin basically delays absorption

262
00:11:02.250 --> 00:11:04.290
till it gets down past the stomach

263
00:11:04.290 --> 00:11:06.570
and you want it onboard as quickly as possible.

264
00:11:06.570 --> 00:11:08.583
So chew that little rascal up.

265
00:11:09.750 --> 00:11:13.050
So the 2014 guidelines, which seem dated,

266
00:11:13.050 --> 00:11:14.370
I mean they're now 10 years old

267
00:11:14.370 --> 00:11:15.780
but nothing much has changed.

268
00:11:15.780 --> 00:11:18.930
But these are the most current NSTEMI

269
00:11:18.930 --> 00:11:21.420
acute coronary syndrome guidelines.

270
00:11:21.420 --> 00:11:25.080
Basically separate things out to an ischemia guided strategy

271
00:11:25.080 --> 00:11:27.750
and an early invasive strategy.

272
00:11:27.750 --> 00:11:30.210
And you'll notice that they're exactly the same

273
00:11:30.210 --> 00:11:32.160
until you get down to group four,

274
00:11:32.160 --> 00:11:34.050
which basically says you give a two B,

275
00:11:34.050 --> 00:11:35.520
three A receptor blocker,

276
00:11:35.520 --> 00:11:37.800
which is another anti-platelet drug,

277
00:11:37.800 --> 00:11:39.180
just a different mechanism

278
00:11:39.180 --> 00:11:41.340
and they're going to the cath lab.

279
00:11:41.340 --> 00:11:42.390
That is the only difference.

280
00:11:42.390 --> 00:11:45.450
But the commonalities in all of them, always give aspirin,

281
00:11:45.450 --> 00:11:47.310
non-enteric coated, chewable,

282
00:11:47.310 --> 00:11:48.870
even if it's not the good tasting,

283
00:11:48.870 --> 00:11:51.990
you know the orange one, you can still chew up aspirin,

284
00:11:51.990 --> 00:11:55.650
P2Y12 inhibitor clopidogrel is most often used.

285
00:11:55.650 --> 00:11:57.540
Remember that one has to be loaded.

286
00:11:57.540 --> 00:11:59.580
And then anticoagulation with heparin,

287
00:11:59.580 --> 00:12:02.790
either unfractionated or low molecular weight,

288
00:12:02.790 --> 00:12:05.400
in many cases someone's going quickly to the cath lab.

289
00:12:05.400 --> 00:12:07.170
We end up using unfractionated heparin

290
00:12:07.170 --> 00:12:10.050
'cause you can turn it on and off more quickly.

291
00:12:10.050 --> 00:12:11.550
But that's always the case.

292
00:12:11.550 --> 00:12:13.530
Whether you're doing a less invasive

293
00:12:13.530 --> 00:12:14.850
or a more invasive strategy,

294
00:12:14.850 --> 00:12:16.650
those three are always on board.

295
00:12:16.650 --> 00:12:19.080
And then the question is, do they go to the cath lab?

296
00:12:19.080 --> 00:12:21.420
And thankfully it's not us typically making that decision.

297
00:12:21.420 --> 00:12:23.610
You don't call your consultant cardiologist

298
00:12:23.610 --> 00:12:26.310
and say hi, I want you to take this person to the cath lab.

299
00:12:26.310 --> 00:12:29.340
You discuss the patient and they make the decision.

300
00:12:29.340 --> 00:12:32.370
So when does the invasive strategy win out?

301
00:12:32.370 --> 00:12:34.860
Meaning when are you pushing

302
00:12:34.860 --> 00:12:37.080
or you know, when is the cardiologist thinking

303
00:12:37.080 --> 00:12:40.320
that they need to go to the cath lab more quickly?

304
00:12:40.320 --> 00:12:41.970
Don't memorize these please.

305
00:12:41.970 --> 00:12:43.290
I'm just gonna run through them quickly.

306
00:12:43.290 --> 00:12:45.270
They're kind of common sense.

307
00:12:45.270 --> 00:12:47.310
Someone's not responding well to treatment.

308
00:12:47.310 --> 00:12:48.870
You've done everything you can

309
00:12:48.870 --> 00:12:52.110
and they still have crushing sternal chest pain.

310
00:12:52.110 --> 00:12:53.550
They've had previous intervention

311
00:12:53.550 --> 00:12:56.403
and they're not amenable to a repeat PCI.

312
00:12:57.420 --> 00:12:59.973
If they've got heart failure, serious arrhythmias,

313
00:13:01.020 --> 00:13:04.080
significant LV dysfunction, which you have to know already.

314
00:13:04.080 --> 00:13:07.320
They've got big anterior or multiple perfusion defects.

315
00:13:07.320 --> 00:13:09.930
You might know that from a nuclear stress,

316
00:13:09.930 --> 00:13:12.090
high risk TIMI or GRACE score.

317
00:13:12.090 --> 00:13:13.710
Other ways to categorize

318
00:13:13.710 --> 00:13:16.620
or classify someone in terms of their risk

319
00:13:16.620 --> 00:13:19.890
of bad things happening or markedly elevated troponin,

320
00:13:19.890 --> 00:13:22.050
which there's no actual numbers to say

321
00:13:22.050 --> 00:13:23.730
what is markedly elevated.

322
00:13:23.730 --> 00:13:25.680
A troponin of two or three doesn't really count

323
00:13:25.680 --> 00:13:27.510
when you're getting numbers in the fifties and sixties,

324
00:13:27.510 --> 00:13:29.060
you've got someone's attention.

325
00:13:30.990 --> 00:13:32.520
So there's not a question involved with this,

326
00:13:32.520 --> 00:13:33.720
but just so we're clear on

327
00:13:33.720 --> 00:13:36.213
what an ST elevation MI looks like.

328
00:13:37.050 --> 00:13:39.210
Lemme do this side here.

329
00:13:39.210 --> 00:13:42.240
Hopefully the 10 seconds would've been enough

330
00:13:42.240 --> 00:13:43.590
to glance over at this

331
00:13:43.590 --> 00:13:47.010
and say yikes, V two, V three, V four, V five,

332
00:13:47.010 --> 00:13:51.840
V six looks okay but big antreceptal MI,

333
00:13:51.840 --> 00:13:53.460
even stretching out with V five.

334
00:13:53.460 --> 00:13:55.740
You'd suggest that that's coming out to the lateral wall.

335
00:13:55.740 --> 00:13:58.620
So in this case gonna be LAD territory.

336
00:13:58.620 --> 00:14:00.000
If you're getting out to the lateral wall

337
00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:02.490
thinking circumflex involved as well.

338
00:14:02.490 --> 00:14:05.040
Concern this could actually be a left main lesion.

339
00:14:05.040 --> 00:14:06.420
This is a bad MI.

340
00:14:06.420 --> 00:14:09.480
So ST segment elevation, you may see

341
00:14:09.480 --> 00:14:12.570
with ST elevation MI we don't in this particular EKG,

342
00:14:12.570 --> 00:14:15.180
but you may see some corresponding

343
00:14:15.180 --> 00:14:18.570
or some collateral ST segment depression.

344
00:14:18.570 --> 00:14:20.640
What are termed reciprocal changes.

345
00:14:20.640 --> 00:14:21.750
The opposite of up,

346
00:14:21.750 --> 00:14:25.050
the opposite of ST elevation is ST depression.

347
00:14:25.050 --> 00:14:26.190
Just as with ischemia,

348
00:14:26.190 --> 00:14:30.150
the ST depression doesn't necessarily imply ischemia

349
00:14:30.150 --> 00:14:31.230
in that particular area.

350
00:14:31.230 --> 00:14:33.750
It is simply termed a reciprocal change

351
00:14:33.750 --> 00:14:35.667
that goes along with the ST elevation.

352
00:14:37.580 --> 00:14:39.780
So ST elevation occurs

353
00:14:39.780 --> 00:14:42.120
almost immediately post plaque rupture,

354
00:14:42.120 --> 00:14:43.410
actually had an individual we were

355
00:14:43.410 --> 00:14:46.470
in the ED admitting with our residency team

356
00:14:46.470 --> 00:14:49.350
and this fellow got brought in with chest pain,

357
00:14:49.350 --> 00:14:50.940
was talking with us, kind of animated.

358
00:14:50.940 --> 00:14:53.070
We're going along and getting his whole history

359
00:14:53.070 --> 00:14:55.950
and as we're talking he's becoming less animated,

360
00:14:55.950 --> 00:14:59.220
looking more ashen, starting to look a little diaphoretic.

361
00:14:59.220 --> 00:15:00.510
The residents, they're talking with him,

362
00:15:00.510 --> 00:15:02.010
I'm standing there watching the monitors,

363
00:15:02.010 --> 00:15:04.500
his ST segments are starting to push their way up.

364
00:15:04.500 --> 00:15:05.550
It's like, you know what,

365
00:15:05.550 --> 00:15:07.590
we're not gonna be the admitting service here anymore.

366
00:15:07.590 --> 00:15:10.233
We called a code STEMI and cardiology took that one.

367
00:15:11.280 --> 00:15:13.230
But the ST segment elevation happens,

368
00:15:13.230 --> 00:15:16.878
as plaque rupture occurs, it can be very quick.

369
00:15:16.878 --> 00:15:19.710
As ST segments come back down to baseline,

370
00:15:19.710 --> 00:15:22.020
that typically suggests that you have reperfusion.

371
00:15:22.020 --> 00:15:23.880
It's a positive sign.

372
00:15:23.880 --> 00:15:26.550
Persistent elevation, even though troponins peaked

373
00:15:26.550 --> 00:15:28.080
and heading its way back down,

374
00:15:28.080 --> 00:15:30.210
persistent ST elevation makes you worry

375
00:15:30.210 --> 00:15:31.923
about a ventricular aneurysm.

376
00:15:33.060 --> 00:15:37.020
Q waves are the kinda the end point of an ST elevation MI.

377
00:15:37.020 --> 00:15:39.930
If you think of a Q wave being, I was gonna say a red flag,

378
00:15:39.930 --> 00:15:41.400
but it's actually more like a black flag

379
00:15:41.400 --> 00:15:44.400
that says here's an area of dead muscle

380
00:15:44.400 --> 00:15:46.620
'cause dead muscle doesn't make electricity.

381
00:15:46.620 --> 00:15:48.630
Q waves are basically an indication

382
00:15:48.630 --> 00:15:51.000
of completed myocardial necrosis

383
00:15:51.000 --> 00:15:53.670
with now non electrically active muscle

384
00:15:53.670 --> 00:15:55.290
and they are permanent.

385
00:15:55.290 --> 00:15:57.840
Importantly also, lemme back up a quick second.

386
00:15:57.840 --> 00:16:01.230
Remember that you can't date an ST elevation MI

387
00:16:01.230 --> 00:16:04.290
based on Q waves unless you have sequential EKGs

388
00:16:04.290 --> 00:16:06.420
and say, you know, two weeks ago it was normal,

389
00:16:06.420 --> 00:16:07.350
there were not Q waves.

390
00:16:07.350 --> 00:16:08.460
Now something happened

391
00:16:08.460 --> 00:16:11.340
and we have Q waves now two weeks later,

392
00:16:11.340 --> 00:16:14.940
okay you had that luxury of the previous EKG which was okay,

393
00:16:14.940 --> 00:16:16.800
but you can't look at a single EKG

394
00:16:16.800 --> 00:16:18.630
and say oh this is a recent MI

395
00:16:18.630 --> 00:16:21.690
or non recent MI, it is Q waves are Q waves.

396
00:16:21.690 --> 00:16:23.220
So if you ever worry, you know,

397
00:16:23.220 --> 00:16:25.050
do people just sound like radiologists

398
00:16:25.050 --> 00:16:26.220
and hedge in a bunch of stuff?

399
00:16:26.220 --> 00:16:27.480
You know, age undetermined,

400
00:16:27.480 --> 00:16:29.480
it's 'cause you can't determine the age.

401
00:16:31.380 --> 00:16:34.260
I had mentioned a couple, you know times which arteries

402
00:16:34.260 --> 00:16:37.800
and which portions of the EKG are involved.

403
00:16:37.800 --> 00:16:40.650
This is just a handy diagram,

404
00:16:40.650 --> 00:16:42.900
right coronary artery gets obviously the right side

405
00:16:42.900 --> 00:16:45.540
of the heart also swings around and gets the inferior wall.

406
00:16:45.540 --> 00:16:47.973
So that's leads two three and AVF,

407
00:16:47.973 --> 00:16:50.280
left main is fairly short.

408
00:16:50.280 --> 00:16:52.980
First takeoff of the left main is the circumflex

409
00:16:52.980 --> 00:16:54.900
which goes out to the lateral wall.

410
00:16:54.900 --> 00:16:57.360
This typically leads V five, V six,

411
00:16:57.360 --> 00:16:59.550
LAD hits the anterior wall

412
00:16:59.550 --> 00:17:01.833
and that's leads V one through V four.

413
00:17:03.060 --> 00:17:06.300
Probably all you need to know about coronary vasculature.

414
00:17:06.300 --> 00:17:09.150
So management of STEMI, reperfusion is the key

415
00:17:09.150 --> 00:17:12.363
and as quickly as possible is always the answer.

416
00:17:13.380 --> 00:17:15.540
Percutaneous coronary intervention is preferred.

417
00:17:15.540 --> 00:17:17.670
Meaning if you are standing here,

418
00:17:17.670 --> 00:17:19.980
you've got a cath lab right next to you over here

419
00:17:19.980 --> 00:17:22.890
and you've got a syringe of thrombolytic right here,

420
00:17:22.890 --> 00:17:24.570
cath lab is always gonna win.

421
00:17:24.570 --> 00:17:28.500
So the thrombolytic is when you don't have a good option

422
00:17:28.500 --> 00:17:31.050
to get someone to the cath lab, if there's some reason

423
00:17:31.050 --> 00:17:33.300
that that's not gonna happen, then you thrombolyse.

424
00:17:33.300 --> 00:17:35.730
However, if you've got the option in front

425
00:17:35.730 --> 00:17:37.440
of you within a reasonable amount of time,

426
00:17:37.440 --> 00:17:38.890
patient goes to the cath lab.

427
00:17:40.260 --> 00:17:42.630
There are, and it's really complicated to me

428
00:17:42.630 --> 00:17:44.610
because there's this whole algorithm

429
00:17:44.610 --> 00:17:47.160
of if your patient is at a PCI

430
00:17:47.160 --> 00:17:49.920
versus non PCI capable hospital,

431
00:17:49.920 --> 00:17:53.310
time from onset of symptoms, time till transport.

432
00:17:53.310 --> 00:17:54.480
There's this whole algorithm

433
00:17:54.480 --> 00:17:56.490
that lets you decide do you keep them

434
00:17:56.490 --> 00:17:59.580
at your non PCI capable hospital and thrombolyse

435
00:17:59.580 --> 00:18:04.580
or do you take time to transport to a PCI capable hospital?

436
00:18:05.430 --> 00:18:06.510
Again, the fortunate thing is

437
00:18:06.510 --> 00:18:08.820
that we're not typically making this decision ourselves.

438
00:18:08.820 --> 00:18:10.320
We're in consultation with one

439
00:18:10.320 --> 00:18:12.900
of our cardiology colleagues saying here's where we are,

440
00:18:12.900 --> 00:18:15.720
here's the onset of symptoms, which way you wanna go.

441
00:18:15.720 --> 00:18:18.470
We can thrombolyse here, we can send them, your choice.

442
00:18:19.590 --> 00:18:23.700
So what happens in the cath lab, stent in most cases

443
00:18:23.700 --> 00:18:26.250
and early, if you look at the progression

444
00:18:26.250 --> 00:18:29.820
of invasive interventional cardiology,

445
00:18:29.820 --> 00:18:31.290
it went from balloon angioplasty,

446
00:18:31.290 --> 00:18:33.300
which is kind of on the left there.

447
00:18:33.300 --> 00:18:34.756
It's basically taking a balloon,

448
00:18:34.756 --> 00:18:37.080
squeezing the balloon open

449
00:18:37.080 --> 00:18:39.600
and kind of expanding that vessel,

450
00:18:39.600 --> 00:18:42.450
then slowly deflating it with some crossed fingers hoping

451
00:18:42.450 --> 00:18:44.790
that the vessel stays open.

452
00:18:44.790 --> 00:18:48.510
Next step is a bare metal stent, which is doing

453
00:18:48.510 --> 00:18:51.030
that same procedure except having a wire scaffolding

454
00:18:51.030 --> 00:18:52.650
that now instead of just luck

455
00:18:52.650 --> 00:18:54.720
and prayers that's holding that vessel open,

456
00:18:54.720 --> 00:18:55.980
you've got a wire scaffold

457
00:18:55.980 --> 00:18:57.873
that is holding everything in place.

458
00:18:58.830 --> 00:19:01.530
The plus and the minus of the bare metal stent is sort

459
00:19:01.530 --> 00:19:03.690
of like when you get a splinter in your finger,

460
00:19:03.690 --> 00:19:06.930
you've got a nidus for clot formation.

461
00:19:06.930 --> 00:19:08.310
A metal scaffold

462
00:19:08.310 --> 00:19:11.340
inside a vessel is an inherently thrombogenic,

463
00:19:11.340 --> 00:19:13.500
clot forming presence.

464
00:19:13.500 --> 00:19:17.520
So the reason that we end up using dual antiplatelet therapy

465
00:19:17.520 --> 00:19:18.750
for bare metal stents is

466
00:19:18.750 --> 00:19:22.350
because you've got this clot formation potential

467
00:19:22.350 --> 00:19:23.490
in the middle of that vessel

468
00:19:23.490 --> 00:19:25.740
and you don't want it to clot off.

469
00:19:25.740 --> 00:19:26.850
What happens over time,

470
00:19:26.850 --> 00:19:28.860
and for a bare metal stent, typically over the course

471
00:19:28.860 --> 00:19:31.920
of one to six months, that bare metal stent,

472
00:19:31.920 --> 00:19:35.160
that metal scaffolding now becomes endothelialized,

473
00:19:35.160 --> 00:19:37.260
covered with a thin layer of endothelium

474
00:19:37.260 --> 00:19:40.200
that now takes away the visible metal,

475
00:19:40.200 --> 00:19:42.180
it's incorporated into the vessel wall

476
00:19:42.180 --> 00:19:45.423
and so you don't have a nidus for clot formation anymore.

477
00:19:46.440 --> 00:19:47.820
The problem there is that

478
00:19:47.820 --> 00:19:49.860
because that stent deployment is

479
00:19:49.860 --> 00:19:52.380
an inherently inflammatory process,

480
00:19:52.380 --> 00:19:53.790
as is the acute coronary symptom

481
00:19:53.790 --> 00:19:56.820
that likely triggered the stent to be placed,

482
00:19:56.820 --> 00:19:59.550
that inflammatory process can trigger endothelialization

483
00:19:59.550 --> 00:20:01.050
to progress more rapidly.

484
00:20:01.050 --> 00:20:02.280
And you end up, instead

485
00:20:02.280 --> 00:20:05.730
of having instant thrombosis clot formation,

486
00:20:05.730 --> 00:20:07.680
you end up with instant stenosis,

487
00:20:07.680 --> 00:20:11.100
which is essentially overly exuberant endothelialization.

488
00:20:11.100 --> 00:20:12.570
So now you've got this vessel

489
00:20:12.570 --> 00:20:14.180
and now there's a bare metal stent

490
00:20:14.180 --> 00:20:16.860
or a stent embedded in the vessel wall

491
00:20:16.860 --> 00:20:19.110
and you get instead of a little endothelium,

492
00:20:19.110 --> 00:20:20.880
a lot more endothelium.

493
00:20:20.880 --> 00:20:24.180
So bare metal stents have a greater risk of progression

494
00:20:24.180 --> 00:20:26.310
to instant stenosis.

495
00:20:26.310 --> 00:20:28.350
Basically the vessel re-closing.

496
00:20:28.350 --> 00:20:30.570
So that's where drug-eluting stents come in

497
00:20:30.570 --> 00:20:32.310
and also pay attention to the spelling.

498
00:20:32.310 --> 00:20:36.690
It's eluting with a T, meaning they leak out drug,

499
00:20:36.690 --> 00:20:39.210
eluding with a D is what happens when you steal something

500
00:20:39.210 --> 00:20:40.610
and you run from the police.

501
00:20:41.790 --> 00:20:45.000
So what the drug-eluting stent does is it basically delays

502
00:20:45.000 --> 00:20:46.740
that endothelialization

503
00:20:46.740 --> 00:20:49.650
and it holds it off until there's less inflammation

504
00:20:49.650 --> 00:20:54.650
and the vessel is less likely to develop instant stenosis.

505
00:20:54.780 --> 00:20:57.810
But because it stays looking like a bare metal stent longer,

506
00:20:57.810 --> 00:21:00.660
there's a longer time that there's metal exposed,

507
00:21:00.660 --> 00:21:02.640
longer time that there's the risk

508
00:21:02.640 --> 00:21:05.640
for thrombogenesis or clot formation.

509
00:21:05.640 --> 00:21:07.200
So with the drug-eluting stent,

510
00:21:07.200 --> 00:21:09.270
we use dual anti antiplatelet therapy longer

511
00:21:09.270 --> 00:21:11.310
because it takes longer for that drug to go away

512
00:21:11.310 --> 00:21:13.170
and then finally to endothelialyse

513
00:21:13.170 --> 00:21:15.543
and no longer be a metal stent.

514
00:21:16.830 --> 00:21:19.170
So what to do with dual antiplatelet therapy?

515
00:21:19.170 --> 00:21:20.250
This is a key point here.

516
00:21:20.250 --> 00:21:24.810
So it depends on what the trigger for the stent deployment

517
00:21:24.810 --> 00:21:26.880
or stent implantation was.

518
00:21:26.880 --> 00:21:29.340
If it was kind of like a scheduled stent,

519
00:21:29.340 --> 00:21:31.500
someone didn't come in with acute coronary syndrome,

520
00:21:31.500 --> 00:21:33.960
they've been having kind of this on and off angina,

521
00:21:33.960 --> 00:21:35.790
they end up having an angiogram

522
00:21:35.790 --> 00:21:37.800
and by the way they happen to have a vessel

523
00:21:37.800 --> 00:21:41.460
that's narrowed enough that they're gonna deploy a stent.

524
00:21:41.460 --> 00:21:44.610
So if that's the case, stable coronary disease,

525
00:21:44.610 --> 00:21:46.530
that's where the one in six month,

526
00:21:46.530 --> 00:21:47.820
bare metal stent gets one month

527
00:21:47.820 --> 00:21:49.410
of dual antiplatelet therapy.

528
00:21:49.410 --> 00:21:51.720
Drug-eluting stent six months,

529
00:21:51.720 --> 00:21:55.170
a lower time of drug-eluting, excuse me,

530
00:21:55.170 --> 00:21:58.800
of dual antiplatelet therapy than if the same procedure is

531
00:21:58.800 --> 00:22:01.650
done in the midst of an ACS situation.

532
00:22:01.650 --> 00:22:03.300
So if there's acute coronary syndrome,

533
00:22:03.300 --> 00:22:05.940
it's a higher risk for bad things happening.

534
00:22:05.940 --> 00:22:08.280
Dual antiplatelet therapy is continued on longer

535
00:22:08.280 --> 00:22:09.573
up to 12 months.

536
00:22:12.060 --> 00:22:15.540
There are three P2Y12 inhibitors.

537
00:22:15.540 --> 00:22:18.240
Again platelet inhibitors just by a different mechanism.

538
00:22:18.240 --> 00:22:19.920
Everyone's familiar with clopidogrel,

539
00:22:19.920 --> 00:22:22.980
brand name Plavix, the handy thing here.

540
00:22:22.980 --> 00:22:26.520
So they go from clopidogrel, which is a prodrug

541
00:22:26.520 --> 00:22:30.660
and its metabolism is influenced heavily by 2C19,

542
00:22:30.660 --> 00:22:31.830
meaning it can be inhibited

543
00:22:31.830 --> 00:22:34.400
and therefore it doesn't get converted from a prodrug

544
00:22:34.400 --> 00:22:37.113
to a regular drug, or the active form.

545
00:22:38.070 --> 00:22:40.800
Prasugrel, which is next down is also a prodrug

546
00:22:40.800 --> 00:22:43.110
but it's not as easily inhibited.

547
00:22:43.110 --> 00:22:45.543
And then finally, Ticagrelor is not a prodrug.

548
00:22:46.500 --> 00:22:48.300
They also go from top to bottom.

549
00:22:48.300 --> 00:22:51.060
Not only are they alphabetical, which makes it handy,

550
00:22:51.060 --> 00:22:54.840
but they go from the least effective to the most effective.

551
00:22:54.840 --> 00:22:56.250
So Ticagrelor is actually

552
00:22:56.250 --> 00:22:59.370
the most aggressive antiplatelet drug that there is,

553
00:22:59.370 --> 00:23:02.250
Prasugrel's in the middle, clopidogrel's at the least

554
00:23:02.250 --> 00:23:05.670
and they're alphabetical at least the generic names are.

555
00:23:05.670 --> 00:23:07.830
So if that helps to organize them,

556
00:23:07.830 --> 00:23:09.660
at least it does in my brain.

557
00:23:09.660 --> 00:23:13.020
Who ends up with bypass surgery, left main disease

558
00:23:13.020 --> 00:23:16.446
'cause it's hard to stent the left main coronary artery.

559
00:23:16.446 --> 00:23:17.940
Three vessel disease.

560
00:23:17.940 --> 00:23:22.320
And one of the biggies is patients with diabetes.

561
00:23:22.320 --> 00:23:24.360
Patients with diabetes tend to have

562
00:23:24.360 --> 00:23:26.790
rather than a single area of stenosis

563
00:23:26.790 --> 00:23:29.730
that you can easily stent or easily bypass,

564
00:23:29.730 --> 00:23:32.100
they tend to have more diffuse disease,

565
00:23:32.100 --> 00:23:33.960
big long areas of stenosis.

566
00:23:33.960 --> 00:23:35.400
And those patients tend to do better

567
00:23:35.400 --> 00:23:37.743
with bypass surgery than they do with PCI.

568
00:23:39.210 --> 00:23:41.153
All right, let's move to another question.

569
00:23:42.150 --> 00:23:45.330
Got a 52-year-old man who's got an acute MI

570
00:23:45.330 --> 00:23:47.100
for which he had PCI with placement

571
00:23:47.100 --> 00:23:48.930
of two drug-eluting stents.

572
00:23:48.930 --> 00:23:51.270
Echo shows his EF is 35%.

573
00:23:51.270 --> 00:23:54.810
He started on numerous medications at discharge, which one

574
00:23:54.810 --> 00:23:57.660
of the following is more useful for symptom control

575
00:23:57.660 --> 00:23:59.253
than for improving mortality.

576
00:24:01.152 --> 00:24:02.929
So we've got atorvastatin, lisinopril,

577
00:24:02.929 --> 00:24:06.530
metoprolol and nitroglycerin, all right, awesome.

578
00:24:10.500 --> 00:24:11.970
So most you're going with nitroglycerin,

579
00:24:11.970 --> 00:24:14.100
which helps people feel better.

580
00:24:14.100 --> 00:24:16.380
Whether or not it saves lives is kind of debatable.

581
00:24:16.380 --> 00:24:17.970
No one's gonna quit using nitroglycerin

582
00:24:17.970 --> 00:24:19.270
'cause people feel better.

583
00:24:20.580 --> 00:24:24.960
These are the four that you have to know, post MI,

584
00:24:24.960 --> 00:24:27.810
there are four classes of drugs that improve survival.

585
00:24:27.810 --> 00:24:30.090
ACE inhibitors and ARBs will be the, you know,

586
00:24:30.090 --> 00:24:32.220
in there as well beta blocker, statins

587
00:24:32.220 --> 00:24:35.670
and an antiplatelet drug aspirin, ideally,

588
00:24:35.670 --> 00:24:37.500
I feel like these are the four drugs that if you try

589
00:24:37.500 --> 00:24:40.920
to send some patient home from the hospital without

590
00:24:40.920 --> 00:24:43.860
an element of each or one of these four classes of drugs,

591
00:24:43.860 --> 00:24:47.190
the EHR will lock the hospital doors, ready to discharge,

592
00:24:47.190 --> 00:24:49.470
click send, nope, not gonna happen.

593
00:24:49.470 --> 00:24:51.660
Are you sure you don't wanna prescribe all four of these?

594
00:24:51.660 --> 00:24:54.460
I'm positive, locking doors now, patient will not leave.

595
00:24:55.320 --> 00:24:57.030
So those are the four that you have to have.

596
00:24:57.030 --> 00:24:59.970
Those are the four drugs that improve survival post MI.

597
00:24:59.970 --> 00:25:02.580
Again, we talked about dual antiplatelet therapy.

598
00:25:02.580 --> 00:25:05.400
There's a bunch of options that improve symptoms.

599
00:25:05.400 --> 00:25:08.040
Nitroglycerin, calcium channel blockers,

600
00:25:08.040 --> 00:25:09.270
digoxin is a tough one

601
00:25:09.270 --> 00:25:11.400
and the digoxin pendulum obviously swings back

602
00:25:11.400 --> 00:25:14.610
and forth pretty widely over the years.

603
00:25:14.610 --> 00:25:17.463
May improve symptoms, don't necessarily improve survival.

604
00:25:20.130 --> 00:25:22.200
Make sure you can quickly recognize

605
00:25:22.200 --> 00:25:24.540
a left bundle branch block, which when I say quickly,

606
00:25:24.540 --> 00:25:26.463
it's not always super easy.

607
00:25:27.600 --> 00:25:30.480
The minus is that when you're looking for ST

608
00:25:30.480 --> 00:25:33.660
and T wave changes, someone comes to the hospital

609
00:25:33.660 --> 00:25:37.590
with a crushing substernal chest pain, you do an EKG,

610
00:25:37.590 --> 00:25:41.339
you're looking for ST and T wave changes, depolarization

611
00:25:41.339 --> 00:25:42.939
and repolarization abnormalities

612
00:25:43.860 --> 00:25:45.960
and then you see a left bundle branch block which has

613
00:25:45.960 --> 00:25:48.420
that baseline ST and T wave abnormalities.

614
00:25:48.420 --> 00:25:49.530
It becomes very difficult

615
00:25:49.530 --> 00:25:52.770
to know are these changes I'm seeing on the EKG due

616
00:25:52.770 --> 00:25:55.320
to the existing left bundle branch block

617
00:25:55.320 --> 00:25:58.620
or is there something new that's hidden in there?

618
00:25:58.620 --> 00:26:01.320
There are criteria, there's the Sgarbossa criteria

619
00:26:01.320 --> 00:26:03.570
that are used to help differentiate,

620
00:26:03.570 --> 00:26:07.080
are these ST and T wave changes that I'm seeing more likely

621
00:26:07.080 --> 00:26:08.700
due to and left bundle branch block

622
00:26:08.700 --> 00:26:11.070
or more likely due to ischemia.

623
00:26:11.070 --> 00:26:13.110
The minus is that it's really hard to tell

624
00:26:13.110 --> 00:26:15.360
and the ED knows this, those rascals,

625
00:26:15.360 --> 00:26:16.950
'cause they'll see someone with a left bundle branch block,

626
00:26:16.950 --> 00:26:18.600
it's like nope, they gotta come in.

627
00:26:18.600 --> 00:26:21.540
It's like, but you know there was a 22-year-old who has,

628
00:26:21.540 --> 00:26:23.760
you know, this vague chest pain three months ago.

629
00:26:23.760 --> 00:26:24.930
Nope, nope, left bundle branch block,

630
00:26:24.930 --> 00:26:26.850
they're coming in 'cause you recognize

631
00:26:26.850 --> 00:26:29.160
that you can't read the EKG easily

632
00:26:29.160 --> 00:26:31.050
and looking for ischemic changes

633
00:26:31.050 --> 00:26:33.390
when there's a left bundle branch block present.

634
00:26:33.390 --> 00:26:35.850
Previously we had been given guidance

635
00:26:35.850 --> 00:26:37.260
from American College of Cardiology,

636
00:26:37.260 --> 00:26:40.140
American Heart Association that a left bundle branch block

637
00:26:40.140 --> 00:26:42.450
was basically an MI equivalent.

638
00:26:42.450 --> 00:26:45.510
And we've kind of, well we speaking on behalf

639
00:26:45.510 --> 00:26:48.930
of the American Heart Association have gotten away from that

640
00:26:48.930 --> 00:26:51.750
to say an existing left bundle branch block may

641
00:26:51.750 --> 00:26:54.000
not necessarily be an ACS equivalent,

642
00:26:54.000 --> 00:26:55.890
even a new left bundle branch block.

643
00:26:55.890 --> 00:26:57.843
But still it raises concern.

644
00:27:00.750 --> 00:27:01.980
All right, oh I promised this.

645
00:27:01.980 --> 00:27:04.290
So we've got a 45-year-old man complains

646
00:27:04.290 --> 00:27:06.120
of acute sharp chest pain

647
00:27:06.120 --> 00:27:07.500
relieved by leaning forward.

648
00:27:07.500 --> 00:27:10.230
On exam, you hear a pericardial friction rub

649
00:27:10.230 --> 00:27:11.850
and the EKG will follow.

650
00:27:11.850 --> 00:27:14.100
I hope that you already have the diagnosis in mind.

651
00:27:14.100 --> 00:27:17.283
You know what the EKG is gonna look like, here it is.

652
00:27:20.220 --> 00:27:22.560
I will reassure you that the EKGs that,

653
00:27:22.560 --> 00:27:24.330
I mean you've taken the board exam before probably,

654
00:27:24.330 --> 00:27:26.850
but the EKGs are usually fairly straightforward.

655
00:27:26.850 --> 00:27:29.490
I've never run into one that I thought was like,

656
00:27:29.490 --> 00:27:31.110
oh my gosh, that is so subtle.

657
00:27:31.110 --> 00:27:33.720
How in the world can you call that an example of this?

658
00:27:33.720 --> 00:27:37.773
It is usually diffuse ST segment elevation.

659
00:27:39.000 --> 00:27:42.660
All right, so what is the most appropriate treatment?

660
00:27:42.660 --> 00:27:45.090
We're assuming that you know what the diagnosis is.

661
00:27:45.090 --> 00:27:46.190
What are you gonna do?

662
00:27:48.120 --> 00:27:49.410
It's got nitrates, NSAIDs,

663
00:27:49.410 --> 00:27:51.723
beta blockers or glucocorticoids.

664
00:27:59.580 --> 00:28:00.810
Oh wow, you guys are super fast.

665
00:28:00.810 --> 00:28:02.760
So most are going with NSAIDs, awesome.

666
00:28:04.110 --> 00:28:05.880
Usually viral pericarditis,

667
00:28:05.880 --> 00:28:08.640
usually viral, sometimes idiopathic.

668
00:28:08.640 --> 00:28:10.530
The classic description is the chest pain

669
00:28:10.530 --> 00:28:12.000
is relieved by sitting forward.

670
00:28:12.000 --> 00:28:13.470
It's an inflammatory process.

671
00:28:13.470 --> 00:28:16.353
Therefore we use anti-inflammatory medications.

672
00:28:17.250 --> 00:28:18.752
Indomethacin is the prototype

673
00:28:18.752 --> 00:28:21.270
kind of the gold standard here.

674
00:28:21.270 --> 00:28:23.490
It's also the gold standard for GI upset.

675
00:28:23.490 --> 00:28:25.860
So you might consider something other than indomethacin

676
00:28:25.860 --> 00:28:28.203
but an NSAID is the drug of choice.

677
00:28:29.790 --> 00:28:31.560
All right, oh we're doing great on time.

678
00:28:31.560 --> 00:28:33.660
Let's move on to hyperlipidemia, shall we?

679
00:28:35.940 --> 00:28:39.180
These are the 2013 cholesterol guidelines.

680
00:28:39.180 --> 00:28:42.320
There is a 2017 update which didn't change these

681
00:28:42.320 --> 00:28:43.410
so I'm still keeping it

682
00:28:43.410 --> 00:28:47.310
just so we're the same, keeping this here.

683
00:28:47.310 --> 00:28:50.310
Bottom line is what happened is we totally upended

684
00:28:50.310 --> 00:28:51.330
how we approached lipids

685
00:28:51.330 --> 00:28:53.520
and how we approach hyperlipidemia.

686
00:28:53.520 --> 00:28:56.040
Rather than a total numbers driven approach,

687
00:28:56.040 --> 00:28:57.900
it ended up being a risk driven approach.

688
00:28:57.900 --> 00:28:59.970
And so we were given

689
00:28:59.970 --> 00:29:03.210
and still have four statin benefit groups

690
00:29:03.210 --> 00:29:05.340
and they all make sense when you think about them.

691
00:29:05.340 --> 00:29:07.710
Group one is secondary prevention.

692
00:29:07.710 --> 00:29:09.510
Someone has already existing

693
00:29:09.510 --> 00:29:12.270
atherosclerotic cardiovascular disease, we don't even need

694
00:29:12.270 --> 00:29:14.310
to do a risk calculation, we don't need to do anything.

695
00:29:14.310 --> 00:29:17.160
We recognize that they've got disease, they're high risk,

696
00:29:17.160 --> 00:29:18.900
they need a statin.

697
00:29:18.900 --> 00:29:21.480
Group two, LDL above 190.

698
00:29:21.480 --> 00:29:24.510
That's an untreated LDL basically says this is

699
00:29:24.510 --> 00:29:27.570
an individual who has very likely a familial disorder.

700
00:29:27.570 --> 00:29:29.850
They are at high risk for atherosclerotic disease.

701
00:29:29.850 --> 00:29:31.620
They get treated.

702
00:29:31.620 --> 00:29:35.280
Group three and you'll notice the age 40 to 75,

703
00:29:35.280 --> 00:29:36.990
which never is meant to imply

704
00:29:36.990 --> 00:29:40.260
that we don't use statins in someone under age 40

705
00:29:40.260 --> 00:29:43.830
or that ASCVD risks somehow magically evaporates

706
00:29:43.830 --> 00:29:45.570
after age 75.

707
00:29:45.570 --> 00:29:48.000
It just says when we're being very evidence-based,

708
00:29:48.000 --> 00:29:50.190
40 to 75 is where the data is

709
00:29:50.190 --> 00:29:52.290
and what to do on the other ends

710
00:29:52.290 --> 00:29:56.370
of those age brackets is always a matter of debate.

711
00:29:56.370 --> 00:29:58.860
So age 40 to 75 with diabetes

712
00:29:58.860 --> 00:30:01.887
and LDL is less than 190

713
00:30:01.887 --> 00:30:03.630
'cause otherwise they'd fall into group two.

714
00:30:03.630 --> 00:30:07.110
So if you happen to find someone with diabetes

715
00:30:07.110 --> 00:30:09.030
who has like a perfect LDL

716
00:30:09.030 --> 00:30:12.087
and I guess then you could consider not using a statin.

717
00:30:12.087 --> 00:30:14.340
But that's group three, group four

718
00:30:14.340 --> 00:30:15.960
without clinical disease, without diabetes.

719
00:30:15.960 --> 00:30:17.760
So they're not in group one or group three,

720
00:30:17.760 --> 00:30:18.780
they're in the right age group.

721
00:30:18.780 --> 00:30:20.910
Their LDL doesn't fall into group two,

722
00:30:20.910 --> 00:30:23.190
but you've calculated their estimated tenure risk

723
00:30:23.190 --> 00:30:25.980
and it's 7.5% or greater.

724
00:30:25.980 --> 00:30:28.680
Recognize ACC/AHA uses 7.5%

725
00:30:28.680 --> 00:30:30.810
as their statin threshold.

726
00:30:30.810 --> 00:30:32.640
Different organizations, I always think

727
00:30:32.640 --> 00:30:35.430
of USPSTF being a bit more conservative

728
00:30:35.430 --> 00:30:39.384
and they use a threshold of 10%, 10 year risk

729
00:30:39.384 --> 00:30:40.217
as their statin threshold.

730
00:30:40.217 --> 00:30:42.990
So the seven and half percent is not like carved in stone.

731
00:30:42.990 --> 00:30:44.130
Each organization may come up

732
00:30:44.130 --> 00:30:46.130
with slightly different recommendations.

733
00:30:48.360 --> 00:30:51.270
I purposely made this one look busy because it kind of is.

734
00:30:51.270 --> 00:30:53.310
It's basically saying here are the four groups

735
00:30:53.310 --> 00:30:55.320
and based on those four groups,

736
00:30:55.320 --> 00:30:57.990
how aggressive do you wanna be with a statin?

737
00:30:57.990 --> 00:30:59.760
The deal is it's not all that confusing

738
00:30:59.760 --> 00:31:02.130
'cause almost everybody's high intensity.

739
00:31:02.130 --> 00:31:05.070
So clinical disease, age under 75,

740
00:31:05.070 --> 00:31:07.950
high intensity statin, age over 75,

741
00:31:07.950 --> 00:31:09.930
if there is a problem with a statin,

742
00:31:09.930 --> 00:31:11.640
you wanna dial back to moderate intensity.

743
00:31:11.640 --> 00:31:14.580
You could do that but it's still high intensity

744
00:31:14.580 --> 00:31:15.720
is still preferred.

745
00:31:15.720 --> 00:31:18.510
Group two, familial disorders always high intensity.

746
00:31:18.510 --> 00:31:21.270
Group three, if you happen to find a patient with diabetes

747
00:31:21.270 --> 00:31:24.990
who has an estimated ASCVD risk less than 7.5%, fine,

748
00:31:24.990 --> 00:31:27.180
moderate intensity, everybody else high intensity.

749
00:31:27.180 --> 00:31:30.030
And group four is moderate to high intensity.

750
00:31:30.030 --> 00:31:33.120
So what I would suggest is if someone falls into one

751
00:31:33.120 --> 00:31:34.800
of these four statin benefit groups,

752
00:31:34.800 --> 00:31:37.050
high intensity is the default.

753
00:31:37.050 --> 00:31:38.220
And then you're thinking is this someone

754
00:31:38.220 --> 00:31:40.830
that I could reasonably dial back to moderate intensity

755
00:31:40.830 --> 00:31:42.573
and still be doing them justice?

756
00:31:43.470 --> 00:31:45.570
So there's very few moderate intensity

757
00:31:45.570 --> 00:31:47.400
and the high intensity is easy to remember.

758
00:31:47.400 --> 00:31:48.540
It's only two drugs.

759
00:31:48.540 --> 00:31:50.308
So Atorvastatin, Lipitor 40

760
00:31:50.308 --> 00:31:52.050
and 80 milligrams, Rosuvastatin,

761
00:31:52.050 --> 00:31:55.020
Crestor 20 milligrams are the only drugs

762
00:31:55.020 --> 00:31:59.820
and doses that will reliably decrease LDL by 50% or greater,

763
00:31:59.820 --> 00:32:02.280
bunch of stuff in the moderate intensity category

764
00:32:02.280 --> 00:32:04.443
and drugs that we're all familiar with.

765
00:32:06.510 --> 00:32:09.120
Excuse me, we've got the ASCVD risk calculator.

